SECTION 1: PROJECT INFORMATION A. PROJECT SPECIFIC Special Note: Nothing in this Scope shall preclude federal agencies or federal officials from fulfilling their responsibilities under the National Environmental Policy Act (NEPA), 42 U.S.C.
Section 4321, et seq., or any of NEPA's implementing regulations.
A1.1 INTRODUCTION The Colorado Department of Transportation (CDOT) intends the Consultant to perform the necessary environmental study and associated work efforts to prepare the necessary NEPA documents, currently anticipated to include preparation of a Environmental Impact Statement (EIS) and Record of Decision (ROD), including DEIS, FEIS, and Basic Engineering for the Northwest Corridor.
Sufficient level of design will be required to provide a clear definition of the project, to identify impacts and mitigation measures for the EIS, and to ensure that accurate cost estimates are given.
The Federal Highway Administration (FHWA) is the lead agency for the EIS/Basic Engineering study in cooperation with CDOT.
Work programs, procedures, and products are subject to FHWA review and approval.
A1.2 BACKGROUND Project Description The goal of this project is the examination of interregional transportation needs along this transportation corridor, and the generation of an EIS/ROD which identifies a preferred alternative that best meets those needs, and prepared in coordination with CDOT, RTD, FWHA, local entities, and the public.
Proposed work defined under this contract consists of an evaluation of all reasonable alternatives, including no-action.
Alternatives must consider a full range of possible multimodal options, including possible general transit options, possible improvement of existing roadways, possible new highways and enhancements, possible implementation of a tolling enterprise, as well as Transportation System Management (TSM), and Transportation Demand Management (TDM) items.
Several alternatives are presented in the previously completed "Northwest Quadrant Feasibility Study, Final Report, Management Committee Decision, January 31, 2001 (NWQS)".
Special Note: The noted study represents an informational resource, only.
Neither the mention of this document in this Scope nor the contents of this document are intended to influence the procedures, direction, or results of the environmental studies the Consultant will perform.
It is anticipated that the scope of this environmental study will involve examination of any corridor-relevant (within the limits described in the feasibility study) transportation alternatives appearing in that study.
However, other reasonable alternatives shall not be foreclosed in the environmental study done by the
9
Consultant, and no alternative stated in the feasibility study will be preferred arbitrarily over any other alternative.
Reasonable alternatives must ensure that maximum multi-modal capacity is attained for the corridor's capital investment, possibly including toll lanes, additional replacement/modifications to interchanges and bridges, and improvements to local arterials.
This will ensure that the final preferred alternative is designed to avoid reconstruction if these other improvements are completed at some future date.
Figure 1 illustrates the Northwest Corridor area.
The National Environmental Policy Act (NEPA) requires that environmental impacts be assessed and considered whenever federal funds are used for major transportation projects.
Preparation of an EIS, ROD, and Basic Engineering allows the Northwest Corridor to qualify for federal funds available through FHWA if needed.
Alternative courses of action are required to be assessed in a comparative form in the preparation of the EIS, and decisions shall be made in the best overall public interest based on a balanced consideration of the purpose and need for the proposed action.
The engineering activities will identify spatial requirements for the alternatives under consideration, refine cost estimates, and provide more detailed design plans for the roadway and transit elements.
The design element will be conducted to the extent necessary for complete impact analysis.
The final deliverables will provide a comprehensive evaluation, designed to meet NEPA EIS and ROD preparation requirements of FHWA, focusing specifically on the environmental impacts associated with development of the identified preferred alternative, and determining the appropriate steps toward mitigation of such impacts, if necessary.
CDOT will work cooperatively with the affected cities, agencies, organizations, residents, businesses, and property owners to identify specific alternatives and mitigation that will best meet the needs of the affected area.
As part of this work effort, CDOT will be conducting an extensive community/public outreach effort dedicated to maintain a proactive dialogue with the citizens of the affected communities and to insure that questions and concerns are dealt with quickly and fairly.
CDOT and local jurisdictions have entered into a partnering agreement which will outline roles and responsibilities in this analysis.
A1.3 PROJECT LIMITS The Project Corridor is approximately bounded by the foothills on the west, Simms Street / 96th Street on the east, the intersection of the Northwest Parkway / Tape Drive / Carbon Road / 96th Street on the north, and the intersection of C 470 / I 70 on the south.
The exact project termini may vary during the systems-level analysis.
A1.4 PLANNED IMPROVEMENTS This scope of work has been prepared to define work to be conducted for preparation of an Environmental Impact Statement (EIS) for the Northwest Corridor (between Broomfield and Golden).
This project is within the counties of Boulder, Broomfield, and Jefferson.
Sufficient level of design will be required to define the project, to identify impacts and mitigation
10
measures for the EIS, identify corridors for preservation, and to ensure accurate cost estimates.
