B1.2 GENERAL PROJECT GUIDELINES This scope of work has been carefully reviewed by CDOT staff and contracts personnel and reflects a plan of approach based on the listed goals.
The Consultant is expected to analyze the project goals, evaluate the work elements, and formulate a work plan.
This contract type is a project specific, non-task specific contract to allow work to be "issued" by task order.
The desire is to proceed to a Record of Decision (ROD) but there is no guarantee that task orders will be issued to cover all items in this scope.
The Consultant will be expected to incorporate work elements that may be performed by CDOT personnel.
This process may produce new approaches or modifications to the project work elements.
Authorization to Proceed Work will not commence until the written notice-to-proceed is received by the Consultant.
Routine Reporting and Billing The Consultant will provide the following on a routine basis: 1.
Coordination of all contract activities by the C/PM.
2.
Periodic reports and billings required by CDOT Procedural Directive 400.2.
3.
Minutes of all meetings.
The minutes will be completed and provided to the PMT within five working days after the meeting.
When a definable task is discussed during a meeting, the minutes will identify the "Action Item," the agency responsible for accomplishing it, and the proposed completion date.
In general, all reports and submittals must be accepted by the PMT prior to their content being utilized in follow-up work efforts.
Computer data shall be compatible with CDOT standards.
16
Personnel Qualifications The Consultant Project Manager must be a licensed Professional Engineer, registered with the Colorado State Board of Registration for Professional Engineers and Land Surveyors, and approved by the PMT.
Certain tasks must be done by Licensed Professional Engineers and/or Professional Land Surveyors who are registered with the Colorado State Board of Registration for Professional Engineers and Land Surveyors.
Certain tasks must also be done by a Colorado-licensed Landscape Architect and a certified Industrial Hygienist.
If the consultant will perform surveying on property owned by railroad companies, the consultant must maintain railroad insurance and finance the cost for flagging.
The consultant must also be safety-certified by the railroad companies.
CDOT Computer/Software Information Software used by CDOT includes: Earthwork: Drafting: Survey: Geometry: Bridge: Estimating: Specifications: MxRoad AutoCAD TMOSS (developed by CDOT to convert total Station survey to format CDOT COGO (Coordinate Geometry) Staff Bridge software shall be used in either design or design check Transport (a bid analysis and management systems, an American Association of State Highway 
Computer Data Compatibility CDOT presently utilizes two data formats which Consultants shall be required to use for submitting survey, photogrammetry, and design data: TMOSS (Topography Modeling Survey System) and MxRoad.
The data format used by the Consultant to submit surveying and photogrammetric data shall be as determined by the PMT in coordination with the respective Region PLS.
The data format for submitting design computer files shall be compatible with the MxRoad program.
The Consultant shall immediately notify the PMT if the firm is unable to produce the desired format for any reason and cease work until the problem(s) is (are) resolved.
Refer to Section 5, Submittals, for additional information regarding the MxRoad and TMOSS formats and the acceptable transmittal media.
