Project Standards General Attachment C is a list of technical references applicable to CDOT work.
The Consultant is responsible for ensuring compliance with the listed references.
Conflicts in criteria shall be resolved by the PMT.
Specific Criteria The Consultant shall prepare a list of specific project environmental and design criteria.
The list shall be comprehensive and may include items that are not required for tasks defined in this scope.
The Consultant shall submit the pertinent criteria to the PMT at one of the periodic progress meetings prior to initiating design.
B1.3 WORK ELEMENTS Action Required The goal of the EIS is to evaluate the environmental, social and economic impacts of all reasonable alternatives that address the purpose and need in accordance with NEPA regulations and guidelines.
Additional aspects of multi-modal alternatives may be considered within the EIS based on input received during the agency and public involvement processes and on reasonably expected future funding levels.
This will ensure that the preferred alternative in the EIS is designed to avoid reconstruction if these other improvements are completed at some future date.
Also, the Basic Engineering phase will be completed to carry the description of the project to a "sufficient level of engineering" and to develop a corresponding confidence in the accuracy of the cost estimate.
Members of the consultant team shall make themselves available to meet with interested community groups and organizations.
Public information meetings and/or workshops shall be held throughout development of the DEIS.
Following signature approval of the DEIS by CDOT and FHWA, public hearing(s) shall be held.
Major work elements for this project may include: aerial photographic and ground surveys, environmental analyses, graphics for public display and distribution purposes, analyses of present and projected traffic patterns, evaluation of all types of social, economic and environmental impacts, roadway, tolling options, and supporting engineering studies.
The work elements will be done with sufficient detail to support the recommendation of a preferred alternative in the EIS and to procure a reliable cost estimate for the project implementation.
Investigations and evaluations of social, environmental and economic impacts shall be addressed in the EIS and shall include but not be limited to the following items: Â· Transportation Impacts (highway, transit, bicycle, and pedestrian)
18
