Section 4(f) statement for parks and historic structures, if needed Social (including public safety and security) Economic Environmental Justice Residential and/or business relocations Right-of-way acquisition Hazardous materials Noise Air quality including Congestion Management Assessments and Conformity Land use Wetlands Water quality Ecological resources (vegetation, wildlife) Floodplains 
A preliminary version of the DEIS document will be distributed to CDOT, FHWA, FAA, DOE and the USFWS for review and comments.
Following any necessary revision of the DEIS, CDOT and FHWA must review and approve the DEIS and findings.
Upon completion, the Consultant shall provide a notice for newspaper publication of the time and location of a Public Hearing.
A sufficient number of copies of the DEIS document shall be prepared by the Consultant for distribution to agencies and organizations having jurisdiction in the study corridor and for being made available to the general public for its inspection and review upon advertisement of the Public Hearing.
19
Final Description of Project The environmental documentation will compare impacts of all "build" alternatives to the "noaction" alternative.
The final definition may include: Â· Â· Â· Â· Â· Â· Â· Â· Â· The general description above for both the opening year and the year 2030.
The highway configurations (safety elements, operational elements, bridge replacements, interchange modifications, widenings, shoulders, lane additions, roadway realignments, road closures, etc.).
Bus facility Bus operations plans.
The bikeway configuration and alignment.
Right-of-way requirements.
Disclosure of environmental impacts.
Tolling or Value Express options Commitment of measures to mitigate environmental impacts.
Funding Plan A funding plan shall be prepared that shows estimated project costs for administration, engineering and construction.
Costs shall be indexed to opening year as well as the 2030 design year.
Financing sources shall also be incorporated into the plan, which may affect the overall cost of the project.
Cost Estimate The consultant will provide detailed cost estimates as directed by the PMT.
The estimate will include detailed capital costs, adjustments for inflation, appropriate contingencies and administrative costs.
B1.4 CONSULTANT RESPONSIBILITY The Consultant is responsible for all aspects of the investigation, evaluation, and documentation of the work elements required for preparation of the EIS.
Sub-consultants may be utilized for surveys, right-of-way work, engineering studies, public involvement, traffic control, and investigation of specific aspects of the natural environment.
Basic Engineering will be performed.
At the DEIS level, Basic Engineering will support identification of all types of impacts and benefits for all reasonable alternative improvements and to recommend a preferred alternative for a package of improvements.
The Consultant shall perform work in the following areas: Â· Overall project administration, including cataloging and controlling documents (includes documents provided by CDOT and FHWA).
