B1.6 QUALITY ASSURANCE/QUALITY CONTROL The Consultant shall submit a Quality Assurance/Quality Control Plan to CDOT for approval no later than one month after Notice to Proceed.
The purpose of the document is to verify: Â· Â· Â· All environmental and design attributes meet established industry or agency standards and complies with all applicable jurisdictional codes and requirements; Multi-disciplinary data acquisition and design efforts are coordinated and addressed; and Design is sufficiently complete to produce a reliable cost estimate for the purposes of project funding and supporting the assessments in the Environmental Impact Statement.
The Quality Assurance/Quality Control Plan shall contain: Â· Â· Â· Â· Â· Â· Â· Â· Â· Brief description of the Project and the Project Goals Project Scope of Work Project Team Organization Chart The names of the Project Manager and each major discipline Task Manager One major point of contact from the Consultant who will be responsible for coordination between the Consultant, and CDOT for each major phase of the project The responsibilities of the Project Manager and each Task Manager A contact list for the Consultant's team, CDOT personnel assigned to the project, and agency contacts A detailed account of the filing system to be used for the project A detailed description of the procedures for plans checking, AutoCAD and computer file maintenance.
CDOT will maintain the right to audit the Consultant's compliance to the Quality Assurance/Quality Control Program submitted by the Consultant by periodically reviewing the Consultant's procedures at the offices of the Consultant.
B1.7 PROJECT INITIATION Partnering Program The PMT encourages the foundation of a cohesive partnership with the Consultant and its subcontractors.
This partnership will be structured to draw on the strengths of each
22
organization to identify and achieve mutual goals.
The objectives are effective and efficient contract performance with reciprocal cooperation, and completion within budget, on schedule, and in accordance with the contract.
To implement this partnership initiative the Consultant shall notify the PMT within 10 days after the notice to proceed to meet and plan a partnering development and team-building workshop.
At this planning session, arrangements will be made to determine the facilitator and the workshop, attendees, agenda, duration, and location.
The workshop should be held prior to the commencement of any major work item.
The following persons will be required to attend the workshop: The PMT, and key project personnel; the Consultant's project manager and key project personnel; and the subconsultants' key project personnel.
The Consultant and the PMT at the initial workshop may decide to hold follow-up workshops periodically throughout the duration of the contract as agreed.
The establishment of a partnership charter, which identifies the workshop participants' mutual goals on the project, will not change the legal relationship of the parties to the contract nor relieve either party from any terms of the contract.
In addition, CDOT, as outlined in Appendix E: Memorandum of Understanding, has agreed to a partnership agreement with local jurisdictions.
Field Reconnaissance Trip All key members of the Consultant's team shall participate in a field reconnaissance trip with members of the PMT to review the corridor and to take note of the physical features.
The Consultant shall review all of the standards to be used for the project and shall submit any questions in writing to CDOT.
If the Consultant does not have any questions regarding this scope of work, a statement acknowledging receipt of the documents must also be completed.
The Consultant shall provide CDOT a disk that contains samples of their AutoCAD setup that is compatible with CDOT's criteria.
The Consultant team will participate in the update and refinement in the Project Management Plan.
The Consultant team will be responsible for preparing the Public Involvement Plan and updates, as needed, as well as FTA Section 5309 New Starts Report (during the FEIS process if applicable.)
This phase of the project will also require the Consultant team to organize public scoping meetings rooms (assume 3 meetings), develop advertisements, and pay for ads to appear in the major and local newspapers.
