B1.8 PROJECT MANAGEMENT PLAN If, in addition to FHWA, FTA must be involved in this project, then under Section 14 of the FullFunding Grant Agreement (FFGA), the Project is subject to the Project Management Oversight regulation codified at 49 C.F.R. Part 633.
Subpart C of this regulation at Section 633.21 requires the submission of a Project Management Plan (PMP) as a condition of Federal financial assistance and contemplates that review and approval of the PMP will be part of the Grant review process.
A PMP will be prepared by the Consultant and assistance provided in preparing the Grant application.
The minimum requirements of the PMP are specified in the regulation 49 C.F.R.
Section 633.25.
In promulgating the regulation governing the contents of the PMP, the FTA recognized that the PMP is a dynamic document for managing engineering, design, construction and start-up of a project.
The regulation allows for periodic updates of the PMP as the Grantee implements the Project.
At the Grant application stage, the FTA expects the PMP to provide sufficient detail to evidence the grantee's technical capacity to implement and operate the Project.
The PMP for managing later stages of the Project may be set forth in general terms, together with a statement of how and when the details will be developed; but the Grantee must demonstrate that the PMP will be developed and followed, as necessary, to stay ahead of the implementation of the Project.
The PMP will also address and describe the elements which will be required to support the Full Funding Grant Agreement application, including: Â· Â· Â· Â· Master Schedule QA/QC Plan Configuration Management Plan PE Summary Report
B1.9 PUBLIC INVOLVEMENT PLAN A comprehensive and responsive Public Involvement program is essential to the success of this project.
CDOT and FHWA are committed to an extensive citizens, business, and community organizations involvement process throughout the study duration.
The Consultant shall prepare and implement a Public Involvement Plan that meets the requirements of 23 U.S.C. 128 and creates a process to ensure extensive involvement and input by all stakeholders, interested parties, affected publics, and others into the development and preparation of the Northwest Corridor EIS.
The public involvement process shall be designed to provide meaningful input from the public in the EIS process.
The Public Involvement Plan shall be an early action item and will include the following minimum components:
24
1.
Identify all the stakeholders and affected and interested publics.
The Public Involvement Plan will include a list that is an exhaustive compilation of all the stakeholders and affected and interested publics.
2.
Describe a process designed to maximize involvement and input by all organizations, agencies, and persons on the public involvement list created in item 1 and to provide the foundation for the decision-making process for the project.
The chosen Consultant shall work with the PMT to identify the specific membership of committees proposed for the Public Involvement Process and what role each will play in decision-making for the project.
3.
Include a formal avenue for input by public policy makers and input by technical staff of the agencies and stakeholders such as Policy and Technical Advisory Committees and Executive Oversight Committee Meetings, as used in previous major studies.
The Plan must include a tentative schedule of meeting dates.
These meetings are planned for every other month, but may need to be held more frequently to meet project milestones.
Also, the Consultant must plan to attend monthly Corridors Coordination Meetings and coordinate the agenda and management of the meeting with Consultants on other CDOT major studies that are currently being performed.
4.
Describe a mechanism or procedure to report progress, status, and results of the EIS to the public, the committees, and others involved and to elicit and receive feedback.
This may include, but not be limited to, newsletters, press releases, website(s), hot lines, open houses, and public meetings.
5.
Describe a process for the review and approval of the alternatives, evaluation criteria, and preferred alternative.
The proposed process must be reviewed and approved by the PMT.
As part of the public involvement process, the Consultant must: Â· Â· Conduct a series of Project Scoping Meetings at appropriate locations, to collect input from the various publics regarding the EIS in accordance with the requirements of NEPA.
Describe and include in their cost estimate the specific activities, techniques, formats, and number of meetings to ensure an open and proactive public involvement process.
Design charettes must be included.
The public involvement process must facilitate consensus development and the necessary public meetings and notices as required under NEPA.
The Consultant will be required to prepare all presentational materials to communicate project information, as needed.
