SECTION 2: ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT STATEMENT PROCESS The compilation of the Environmental Impact Statement (EIS) documents for the Northwest Corridor will be in accordance with US Department of Transportation (USDOT) Order 5610.1E, FHWA Federal-Aid Highway Program Guidelines (FHPG), Technical Advisory T 6640.8A, FTA guidance on environmental documentation, applicable FAA regulations, DOE documentation required to preserve right of way, and the Council on Environmental Quality's (CEQ) and FWHA NEPA Regulations, as amended.
The consultant will ensure that the general design characteristics presented in the EIS are practical, feasible and economical.
Design of the project will be completed sufficiently so that design standards and criteria may be evaluated and a cost estimate prepared prior to the approval of the documents.
A. EIS PROCESS The Consultant shall accomplish the following activities:
A2.1 FIRST PRELIMINARY DEIS PREPARATION Scoping will be the first activity, and will be used to identify the range of alternatives and impacts.
The Consultant shall perform the following: 1.
Compile data, analyze impacts and develop appropriate mitigation measures.
Take necessary actions to resolve issues.
2.
Write the DEIS document incorporating the inputs from the social, economic, physical, biological, and environmental investigations.
3.
Coordinate the issues and recommended mitigation with appropriate local government agencies and CDOT personnel.
4.
Prepare a proposed EIS outline for review by CDOT and FHWA.
A2.2 REVIEW AND ADOPTION The Consultant shall perform the following: 1.
Provide draft of the DEIS to CDOT, which CDOT will forward to FHWA for review and comment.
2.
Address comments and concerns resulting from review processes, revise the DEIS as necessary, and resubmit for final review.
30
3.
Forward the completed DEIS for review and signature (not done by the Consultant).
4.
Return title page to Contract Administrator (not done by the Consultant).
A2.3 DEIS DISTRIBUTION, ADVERTISING AND PUBLIC REVIEW The Consultant shall perform the following: 1.
Arrange for the public notice (Notice of Availability).
2.
Provide for public review of the EIS, including placing the document in libraries and with agencies.
Compile public comments.
Draft response to public comments.
A2.4 PUBLIC HEARINGS The Consultant shall: 1.
Advertise the public hearing, hire recording and transciption services, reserve rooms, and prepare the hearing handout and announcement.
The assumption is that two hearings will be held in two separate locations.
Prepare the graphic and handout presentation addressing the following concerns: Â· Â· Â· Â· Â· Â· Â· Â· Purpose and Need for project.
Maps showing the preferred alternative and comparison of other reasonable alternatives considered.
Description of social, environmental, and economic impacts of all reasonable alternatives.
Present design features.
Consistency with federal and local plans.
Timetable for right-of-way acquisition and construction.
Source and amount of funding.
Present mitigation measures.
2.
Attend the Hearings and record the event for transcript.
3.
Prepare a certified, verbatim transcript of the recorded testimony.
B. OTHER EIS PROCESS ELEMENTS B2.1 LAND USE The Consultant shall analyze land use impacts of the preferred alternative at the corridor level.
This analysis shall include consistency with planning and zoning and future comprehensive plans.
31
Assumptions for information developed are (at corridor level): Â· Â· Â· Â· Â· Â· Â· Population Employment Income Population Employment density Major development centers Neighborhood boundaries (by Traffic Analysis Zone).
This scope assumes that DRCOG will provide land use data sets for 2008 and 2030 [check with DRCOG], build and no-build.
B2.2 TRANSPORTATION IMPACTS The Consultant shall define the transportation impacts of the preferred alternative including levels of service, travel time, bicycle issues, reliability, ridership, access, parking, bus service, and traffic mitigation.
This will be done for opening day and the Year 2030.
A separate chapter in the EIS is assumed for this analysis.
B2.3 VISUAL ANALYSIS The Consultant shall provide a design that enhances the beauty as well as the utility of the proposed construction.
This may include, but not be limited to: configuration considerations to enhance views of the scenic, open space character of the surrounding environment; architectural treatments for major structures; and landscaping treatments.
Alternative typical sections, vertical and horizontal alignments, and intersection/interchange concepts shall be evaluated for their aesthetic impact, considering access to adjacent areas and impacts on existing and future adjacent development.
Preliminary sketch concepts of structures and landscape improvements shall be developed for each design concept analyzed in the Concept Study.
These shall include conceptual plan and elevation drawings of highway, pedestrian, rail, bridge structures, planting masses, and plans illustrating access and development potential of adjacent areas.
Consideration shall be given to relative visual qualities of the alternatives, including visual impacts of proposed improvements on adjacent areas and views from the roadway transit facility.
Determination of visual impacts of the views toward the new facilities from adjacent areas and on views from the new facilities shall be made as part of the alternatives analysis.
Each simulation will contain a "before" and "after" illustration of existing conditions and the proposed design.
32
SECTION 3: PROJECT DEVELOPMENT The following section includes detailed work descriptions for all tasks to be accomplished during preparation of the Northwest Corridor EIS.
A. PROJECT INITIATION AND CONTINUING REQUIREMENTS A3.1 INITIAL PROJECT MEETING An initial meeting will be held and an on-site inspection (when appropriate) will be made to ensure that the Consultant is familiar with the existing conditions as well as the project requirements.
This meeting will be coordinated by the Consultant and conducted by the PMT.
The Consultant will send notices for the meeting from a list provided by the PMT.
A3.2 REVIEW ENVIRONMENTAL MITIGATION Minimize and mitigate requirements and ensure that they are included in the plan for design.
A3.3 INDEPENDENT DESIGN REVIEW An independent design review shall be performed on the design accomplished by others that will be used in this project.
A3.4 PROJECT SCHEDULE Develop an aggressive Project Schedule, in consultation with CDOT, using environmental streamlining techniques, and assign tasks.
A3.5 DEVELOP DESIGN CRITERIA Submit a copy of Attachment D with the appropriate items completed.
A3.6 INITIATE SURVEY Arrange Preliminary Field Survey and Aerial Survey.
The Survey Manual provides an agenda for the Pre-Survey Conference.
A3.7 RIGHT OF ENTRY and PERMITS Land Not Controlled by CDOT Some activities may require work on land that is not controlled by the CDOT.
In such cases the Consultant shall obtain the necessary written permission to enter the premises.
Included in this written permission will be the names and telephone numbers of persons to contact should notification prior to entry be necessary.
These written permissions will be applied to CDOT 33
personnel as well as Consultant personnel.
CDOT Form 730 may be used for this purpose.
Signed copies of the written permission will be submitted to the PMT prior to entering private property for survey work.
Access Permits, that include requirements for railroad safety training, insurance, and railroad flaggers may be required by the railroad companies for permission to enter railroad property.
Materials Testing Permits Some activities such as materials testing on existing pavement and structures may require a permit.
Permits will be obtained and copies submitted to the CDOT/PM.
A3.8 TRAFFIC CONTROL Consultant field activities that interfere with traffic operation within existing roadways will require control of existing traffic.
The Consultant will plan and provide any required traffic control for the survey, testing, or design process.
Traffic control operations will be in accordance with the MUTCD and the Colorado Department of Transportation Region 6 Lane Closure Strategy (September 2002).
The Consultant will note that the proposed method for handling traffic must be acknowledged in writing by the PMT.
Also, certification of the Traffic Control Supervisor as a Worksite Traffic Supervisor by the American Traffic Safety Services Association (ATSSA) will be required.
A3.9 INITIAL SUBMITTALS Submit the following samples to the PMT for approval: 1.
An original plan sheet that complies with Section 6, Submittals.
2.
Photogrammetric and/or survey data and a drawing or photograph in accordance with the requirements specified in Section 6 of this scope of work.
NOTE: NO ORIGINAL PLAN SHEETS OR PHOTOGRAMMETRIC SURVEY WORK WILL BE ACCOMPLISHED UNTIL SATISFACTORY SAMPLES HAVE BEEN RECEIVED AND APPROVED BY THE PMT.
A3.10 PROGRESS MEETINGS The PMT and Consultant Project Managers will meet biweekly.
These Progress Meetings will be used to coordinate the work effort and resolve problems and be conducted by the Consultant.
The meetings will review the following: 1.
Activities completed since the last meeting 2.
Problems encountered
