C. CONCEPTUAL DESIGN The following conceptual design development shall be managed by the Consultant to occur along with the communication, project team reviews, data gathering, socioeconomic mitigations, environmental mitigations, and documentation activities in parallel paths as appropriate to complete the process in the minimum time feasible.
C3.1 URBAN PLANNING and AESTHETICS Alternative alignments will be evaluated, considering access to adjacent areas, the creation of open space, and impacts on existing and future adjacent development.
The Consultant will provide conceptual designs for multi-modal paths and open space connections for each alternative.
Planting and open space concepts will be developed.
Landscape/streetscape improvements Develop preliminary sketch concepts of structures and landscape/streetscape improvements for each of the short-listed alternatives.
Develop plan and elevation drawings of bridge structures, planting masses, and plans illustrating access and development potential of adjacent areas for the alternatives to be analyzed in the EIS (assumed to be to-build alternatives).
37
Visual analysis Relative visual qualities of the alternatives, including visual impacts of proposed improvements on adjacent areas and views from the roadway, will be considered.
Determination of minimum visual impacts from adjacent areas and acceptable views from the roadway will be made as part of the alternatives analysis.
Six sketch-photo simulations will be prepared for each alternative in response to expressed public concerns and prominent new features.
Each simulation will contain a "before" and "after" illustration of existing conditions and proposed design.
C3.2 SYSTEM FEASIBILITY STUDY FOR INTERCHANGES If this project proceeds to preparation of a Final EIS, a System Feasibility Study for the entire Northwest Corridor will be prepared in accordance with Procedural Directive 1601.0.
Typically, the System Feasibility Study must consider, as a minimum: alternate routes, accident history, congestion, effects of the interchange on the existing highway system, effects on adjacent interchanges, economic development impact, and local commitment to improving local roadways.
Refer to this Procedural Directive for additional details.
Any modification to the interchange with I 70 will require the preparation and submittal of a FHWA Interstate Access Request.
Special Note: Some or all of the Consultant's possible System Feasibility Study activities may be assigned to take place either antecedent to or concomitantly with activities that are parts of the non-System-Feasibility-Study portions of the Scope.
The purpose of the Procedural-Directive-1601.0-process System Feasibility Study is to provide a comprehensive, responsible, professional analysis under the Procedural Directive 1601 guidelines.
Such a Study is not intended to and will not supplant or contradict any of the results of the NEPA analysis.
A draft study shall be submitted to the PMT for review and comment prior to final submission for transportation commission approval.
C3.3 ALTERNATIVES ANALYSIS Develop Alternatives Develop reasonable range of alternatives that may satisfy the purpose and need of project requirements (see discussion in Section A1.2 Project Description).
If a multi-modal alternative is developed, FTA requires approval of a baseline alternative in order to complete the New Starts rating and allow the project to advance to Preliminary Engineering.
FTA's baseline alternative must be carried through to the entire evaluation.
When required, conceptual layouts will be developed for major structures for each alternate that shows satisfaction of the required span arrangement and the horizontal and vertical clearances.
Examples of items to consider while developing alternatives are multiple modes and transfers between them, alternate routes, accident history, congestion, and effects of the interchange on
38
the existing highway system, effects on adjacent interchanges, economic development impact, and local commitment to improving local roadways.
These alternatives must respond to projected design-year traffic volumes as developed for this scope and for projected ridership on bus service.
Evaluate the impacts of these alternative concepts and the degree to which they fulfill purpose and need.
These concepts will be described schematically and narratively, and reviewed by the PMT.
Screen Alternatives A preliminary screening process will be used on the universe of alternatives to identify a limited number of feasible and significantly different alternatives, which will be subject to more detailed evaluation in Section C3.3 "Test Alternatives Analysis".
The purpose of this screening is to eliminate the obviously unfeasible or unsuitable alternatives.
The criteria used in the preliminary screening should include items identified in Section 3, "D", "Gather Data, Analysis, and Mitigation."
Examples of concerns used in the screening process are environmental (air, noise, water quality, parkland, etc.), historic and archaeological impacts, cost and engineering feasibility, construction staging options, transportation impacts, design-year level of service and other performance measures, socioeconomic impacts and community acceptability, consistency with adopted plans, and urban design issues and opportunities.
The no-action alternative must be carried through the entire evaluation and assessment process.
The Consultant shall develop evaluation criteria related to purpose and need for review and approval by the PMT prior to beginning the screening process.
The design alternatives will be described in a final design alternatives memorandum.
For the set of alternatives, horizontal and vertical alignment studies, at a scale of 1"=200', will be examined.
Test Alternatives Analysis Following the development of the short-list of alternatives, the Consultant shall perform a comprehensive test of each of the short-listed alternatives.
This test shall utilize a decision process, which includes a compilation of all appropriate criteria, as established above.
In addition to the socioeconomic and environmental concerns, the decision criteria shall include design standards.
The criteria will be compiled in coordination with other activities.
Following that, a decision matrix shall be created which combines a list of the alternatives under consideration with the results of the test with each criterion.
39
Complete an Initial Design of the Designated Alternatives Once the alternatives have been tested, general profile and cross section studies will be developed for critical areas to analyze the designated alternatives.
This information shall be sufficient to determine general cut and fill limits, right-of-way and easement requirements, and earthwork and structural requirements.
Design parameters for roadway such as design speeds, maximum grades, typical sections, intersection designs, and pedestrian routing will be determined at the beginning of the study.
The conceptual design for the roadway alignments, detours, and major structures will be completed sufficiently so that preliminary cost estimates can be developed and the satisfaction of pertinent design criteria can be demonstrated.
Necessary variances (design exceptions) will be identified.
The following shall be available following the design: Â· Â· Â· Â· Typical sections and plan and profile of roadway and railway alignments and detours Preliminary hydraulic recommendations Preliminary right-of-way requirements Recommended construction sequence
Perform a Financial Analysis on the Alternatives Designated by the PMT A total cost estimate will be developed for each alternative.
Basic engineering, construction engineering, construction, and maintenance for the design life will be analyzed.
A funding package identifying the funding sources necessary to construct and maintain the project will be developed.
Develop Alternatives (Additional Analysis Requirements) Additional analysis will be done to review impacts related to upgrading the entire corridor to current standards as well as reviewing impacts related to the ultimate reconstruction as required to ensure maximum multi-modal capacity.
Information related to these efforts may not be required for inclusion within the EIS document.
Design options are anticipated to be developed for the following situations: Â· Â· Â· Â· Â· New highway capacity Highway widening Interchange reconfiguration Pedestrian crossings High Occupancy / Toll (HOT) Lanes / other tolling options
40
Test Alternatives Analysis (Additional Analysis Requirements) General profile and cross section studies shall be developed for critical areas to analyze the impacts of each alternative.
Design parameters such as design speeds, maximum grades, typical sections, and intersection designs shall be applied to the extent necessary to evaluate and compare the environmental impacts of the various alternatives.
Designs for the roadways, detours, and major structures, including grade separations, will be completed to a sufficient level so that preliminary cost estimates can be developed and the satisfaction of pertinent design criteria can be demonstrated.
This information must be sufficient, particularly at critical areas, to determine general right-of-way and easement requirements, earthwork and structural requirements, traffic impacts, and preliminary hydraulic recommendations.
Necessary variances shall be identified.
The recommended construction sequence, considering the feasibility of handling traffic during construction, shall be prepared.
A complete cost estimate shall be developed.
Costs shall be analyzed for basic engineering, construction engineering, capital construction costs, right-of-way, operation, and maintenance for the design life.
C3.4 FINAL ALTERNATIVES REPORTS The consultant will complete the determination of the selected alternative.
If specified, a "Final Alternatives Report" will be submitted documenting the analysis process.
This shall include the final staging plan, socioeconomic and environmental concerns, utility conflicts, drainage, right-of-way requirements, and total cost for the recommended alternatives.
NOTE: THE CONSULTANT IS RESPONSIBLE FOR ENSURING THAT THE RECOMMENDED ALTERNATIVE COMPLIES WITH APPLICABLE STANDARDS AND CRITERIA.
WHERE APPROPRIATE, REQUIRED VARIANCES WILL BE IDENTIFIED.
A draft of the report shall be submitted for review and comment prior to the submittal of the final report.
The no action alternative must be carried through the entire evaluation.
C3.5 INTERCHANGE APPROVAL PROCESS.
An interstate access request shall be prepared to obtain access approval from FHWA, as directed by the PMT.
D. GATHER DATA, ANALYSIS, and MITIGATION DEVELOPMENT These activities shall be accomplished in accordance with the PMP concurrently with the other activities in this scope as required.
41
D3.1 TRAFFIC-RELATED ASSIGNMENTS Traffic Study The consultant will obtain the available present-day and design-year traffic volumes for the existing and planned improvements.
When possible, local traffic patterns will be defined.
The data shall include percentage of trucks, directional splits, and turning movements.
The no-build and alternative designs will be analyzed with the traffic projection data to develop the appropriate roadway geometry (i.e., number of lanes, auxiliary lanes, storage lengths, weaving distances, etc.) in accordance with the most recent version of the Highway Capacity Manual.
It may also be necessary for the Consultant to utilize computer simulations to evaluate the more complex areas of the project.
Accident Study The consultant will obtain accident reports and provide the data for the analysis of alternatives.
Noise Study The consultant will prepare a noise assessment analysis in accordance with CDOT Noise Analysis and Abatement Guidelines.
The analysis will consist of the following: Â· Â· Â· Â· Â· Â· Â· Definition of relevant noise abatement criteria and identification of noise-sensitive land uses.
Determination of existing noise levels (by measurement and/or modeling).
Prediction of future traffic-noise levels for all alternatives, including the no-build alternative.
Determination of traffic-noise impact.
Identification and evaluation of feasibility and reasonableness of noise-abatement measures.
Development of recommendations regarding noise-abatement measures.
Consideration of construction-related noise issues.
The above items will be addressed and documented in a technical noise analysis document that will be prepared and submitted to the PMT for review and acceptance.
D3.2 AIR QUALITY-RELATED ASSIGNMENTS Air Quality Modeling The consultant will model air quality for carbon monoxide during the months of December and January to determine project-level conformity.
42
Air Quality Analysis The consultant will prepare an air quality report and submit it to the PMT for acceptance.
Air Quality Analysis (Project Specific) Full air quality analysis is required, including carbon monoxide hot-spot analysis, assuming analysis of the following years: opening year and horizon year (2030).
Both build and noaction alternatives will be modeled.
This scope assumes that the build alternative does not include the addition of flex lanes.
Coordination will occur with the Colorado Air Pollution Control Division (APCD) and EPA and methodology (including number of intersections to be modeled) will be determined at the coordination meetings.
CAL3QHC modeling is required at critical intersections, determined by a screening analysis of intersection volumes and Level of Service (LOS).
This will include intersections adjacent to improved interchanges or other intersections.
All regional and corridor analysis will be done by APCD with modeling information provided by DRCOG.
Air quality analysis will also include a qualitative analysis of on-site bus operations and bus access to park-n-Rides to determine if PM10 hot-spot problems are created.
Mitigation commitments will be developed, as necessary.
D3.3 OTHER TRANSPORTATION SYSTEMS The consultant will evaluate the effect of all transportation systems on the proposed alternatives when appropriate.
D3.4 TRAFFIC RELATED (PROJECT SPECIFIC) Travel Demand Initial travel demand forecasting activities shall include opening day and year 2030 volume projections for roadway and transit facilities.
The year 2030 volume projections shall be used until the 2035 volume projections are available.
Preliminary and no-build and multiple alternative design model runs shall be conducted for opening day and year 2030.
Final no-build and alternative design model runs must be conducted for year 2035 when available.
The different alternative design model runs will test variations of station locations as they relate to specific walk/drive access concepts and bus system interface options.
A Transportation System Management forecast shall also be conducted for year 2030.
The forecasting efforts shall be a joint effort between RTD, DRCOG, and the Consultant.
The Consultant will perform the following modeling tasks: Â· Â· Network coding for both light rail and bus feeder networks.
Travel forecasts for alternatives.
