FHWA and CDOT guidelines will be followed for the mitigation determination.
5.
Prepare a draft noise analysis methodology and assessment report.
This will be reviewed by CDOT OES and Region 6.
A final report will be prepared which includes an appendix with the supporting technical data.
D3.6 TOLL FACILITIES The DEIS will assess the design, operational and financial feasibility, and the public acceptance and use of toll facilities and other potential value pricing implementation options.
The DEIS must also include traffic and revenue modeling for tolling.
Senate Bill 02-197, the comprehensive transportation-funding bill recently passed into state law, allows the Colorado Transportation Commission to create and operate a tolling enterprise as "government-owned business within CDOT".
The tolling enterprise is authorized to toll new or additional capacity for highways.
The potential use of tolling authority or "value pricing" concepts in the Northwest Corridor will be evaluated in the EIS in order to better manage and optimize use of the corridor.
Specific pricing policies will include new construction of toll lanes without an HOV component.
Questions for assessment include, but are not limited to, the following: 1.
Is value pricing both feasible and desirable in the Northwest Corridor ? 2.
What conceptual value pricing options make the most sense?
46
3.
Can value pricing contribute to regional system synergies such as maximizing trip efficiencies on the Northwest Parkway toll road? 4.
Will value pricing help or hinder construction-related and post-construction traffic congestion within the corridor? 5.
How will value pricing coordinate with other possible toll corridors within the metropolitan area?
