D. HYDROLOGY/HYDRAULIC ENGINEERING D4.1 HYDROLOGY 1.
Establish drainage basin data: delineate, determine size, waterway geometric, vegetal cover, land use for the project corridor.
The basin maps for the project area, including Land Use (imperviousness) and Soils (infiltration rates), will be updated to reflect the "Selected Alternative".
Drainage basins will be refined to show minor drainage design points, as well as major drainage features/improvements and outfall design points for the selected alternative.
"Major" will be defined as storm sewer pipes 48 inches in diameter or larger, and peak 100-year flows greater than 500 cfs.
On-site drainage basin maps will be produced at a scale of 1" = 400' for the report (full size at 1" = 200').
Off-site basins will be shown at a scale of 1" = 1000' for the report.
Drainage basin maps shall show existing major drainage improvements, including bridges, culverts and open channels.
The basin maps shall show the extent of the 100-year floodplain.
2.
Collect historical data; research flood history and previous studies and designs in the proximity; and obtain data from other sources (e.g., Urban Drainage 
3.
Select a storm frequency based on the CDOT Design Manual criteria.
The storm frequencies selected shall not conflict with local agency design storm criteria.
68
4.
Using the basin maps completed in Task D4.1, a hydrologic analysis will be performed to establish design flows for all major structures to be included in this phase of the project.
The Rational Method, Colorado Hydrograph Procedure (CUHP), and Urban Design Stormwater Modeling Method (UDSWMM) will be used for the analyses.
The design discharges will be tabulated on the drainage basin maps to be included in the Project Master Drainage Plan.
Input parameters and design calculations will be included in the report appendices.
The analysis will include detention pond routing for regional-type detention and water quality ponds that might be included in the project.
Requirements for detention will be identified for specific sites, but actual site detention designs for these facilities will be left for the final design phase.
The requirements for water quality ponds and sediment control measures will also be identified, but not designed until final design phase.
