H. MAJOR STRUCTURAL DESIGN Major structures are bridges and culverts with a total length greater than twenty feet and retaining walls with a total length greater than fifty feet.
This length is measured along centerline of roadway for bridges and culverts, and along the top of wall for retaining walls.
Their design shall be in accordance with: the AASHTO LRFD Bridge Design Specifications with interims through 2003, the CDOT Bridge Design Manual, and the CDOT Bridge Technical Memorandums .
H4.1 STRUCTURAL DATA COLLECTION Structural data collection shall be in accordance with the CDOT Bridge Design Manual.
H4.2 STRUCTURAL SELECTION and LAYOUT Structural selection and layout shall be in accordance with the CDOT Bridge Design Manual
H4.3 STRUCTURE SELECTION REPORT The Consultant shall prepare a structure selection report in accordance with the CDOT Bridge Design Manual and obtain acceptance by the PMT on the recommended structure and its layout.
Allow approximately four weeks for review of the structure selection report.
The associated general layout, with the revisions required by the PMT review, will be included in the EDR plans.
The work schedule shall be planned accordingly.
The structure selection report, with the associated general layout, must be accepted in writing by the PMT.
H4.4 FOUNDATION INVESTIGATION The Consultant shall initiate the foundation investigation as early in the engineering phase as is practical.
The foundation investigation shall be conducted and incorporated into the design in accordance with the CDOT Bridge Design Manual.
H4.5 STRUCTURAL DESIGN CRITERIA Early in the project, the Consultant shall develop and submit structural design criteria.
H4.6 OTHER STRUCTURAL DESIGN This component shall include the design of grade separation crossings for rail, and related structures.
I. CONSTRUCTION PHASING PLAN A construction phasing plan shall be developed for all projects that integrate the construction of all the project work elements into a practical and feasible sequence.
This plan shall accommodate the existing traffic movements during construction (detours).
Impacts from 75
construction phasing shall be evaluated in the environmental analysis.
A preliminary traffic control plan will also be developed which will be compatible with the phasing plan.
J. ENGINEERING DESIGN REVIEW J4.1 PREPARATION FOR THE ENGINEERING DESIGN REVIEW (EDR) The Consultant shall perform the following: 1.
Coordinate, complete, and compile the plan inputs from other activities: materials, hydraulics, traffic, right-of-way, and major structures.
2.
If major structures are included in the project, a general layout (which has been accepted by the PMT) will be included in the EDR plans.
3.
Prepare the preliminary cost estimate for the work described in the EDR plans based on estimated quantities.
4.
The EDR plans shall comply with the requirements of the CDOT Procedural Directive 514.1 and 1905.1 and will include: title sheet, typical sections, general notes, plan/profile sheets, and preliminary layouts of interchanges/intersections.
The plan/profile sheets will include the following: all existing topography, survey alignments, projected alignments, profile grades, ground line, existing ROW, rough structure notes (preliminary drainage design notes), and existing utility locations.
The following items will be mandatory for the PDR plans: a. preliminary earthwork (plotted cross sections at critical points with roadway template and existing utility lines at known or estimated depths) b. catch points c. proposed right-of-way d. pit data (if required) e. soil profile and stabilization data f. structure general layouts (if appropriate).
Typical plan sheet scales will be: Plan and Profile: 1 Inch = 50 Feet (urban) 1 Inch = 100 Feet (Rural) Intersection: 1 Inch = 20 Feet EDR plans shall be provided in half size (11 inch by 17 inch) format.
5.
The ROW Ownership Map shall be included in the EDR plan set.
6.
The plans shall be submitted to the PMT for a preliminary review prior to the EDR. 7.
The plans will be reproduced by CDOT Reproduction or the Consultant.
76
8.
The construction phasing and the preliminary traffic control plan with proposed detours will be included in the EDR plan set.
J4.2 ENGINEERING DESIGN REVIEW RESPONSIBILITIES The Consultant shall perform the following: 1.
Attend the EDR. 2.
The EDR meeting minutes shall be prepared by the C/PM, approved by the PMT, and distributed as directed.
3.
The EDR original plan sheets shall be revised/corrected in accordance with the meeting comments within sixty (60) working days.
4.
Design decisions concerning questions raised by the EDR will be resolved in cooperation with the PMT.
The C/PM shall document the decision and transmit the documentation to the PMT for approval.
5.
A list of all deviations from standard design criteria along with the written justification for each one shall be submitted to the PMT.
J4.3 POST-CONCEPTUAL DESIGN REVIEW REVISIONS The Consultant shall complete the revisions required by the EDR before this phase of work is considered to be complete.
K. VALUE ENGINEERING A team of experts in the fields of highway design will perform value engineering.
This team will consist of individuals with no prior exposure to the project in order to ensure that their comments are fair and unbiased.
The Value Engineering Teams will be assembled to review the engineering plans.
This information shall be provided to each team at least three weeks in advance of a review meeting to discuss their results.
Each review meeting shall be conducted by an individual with prior experience and certified in facilitating V/E reviews.
Each Agency's Project Manager should also be in attendance.
The results of the review meeting shall be summarized in a report to be prepared by the meeting facilitator and forwarded to the Agency Project Managers that were in attendance during the meeting.
Accordingly, the Agency Project Managers shall prepare a written response as to which certain issues were not included and how all approved V/E results will be incorporated into subsequent engineering efforts.
These responses shall be forwarded to the PMT for final action.
Each VE/Peer review recommendation will be formally evaluated and sufficient justification made for its acceptance or rejection.
All approved changes shall be incorporated into the final Basic Engineering review plans.
77
CDOT will also assemble a group of experts for a Peer Review Team.
The Peer Review Team will include individuals from DOT's and transit agencies around the country who bring experience from similar systems.
The Peer Review Team will convene at least twice, once after Basic Engineering (final definition of project stage) and once near the end of engineering in conjunction with the VE Review.
The Peer Review Team will review and make recommendations as appropriate.
The Consultant will participate in the Peer Review as needed.
78
SECTION 5: SUBMITTALS A. REPORT REQUIREMENTS A5.1 REPORT SUBMITTALS All required reports and studies shall be submitted for review to the PMT.
Final submittals shall incorporate the corrections and/or revisions resulting from the review.
A5.2 FINAL ALTERNATIVES REPORT The Consultant shall ensure that the general design characteristics presented in the Final Alternatives Report are practical, feasible and economical.
Design of the project will be completed sufficiently so that design standards and criteria may be evaluated and a cost estimate prepared prior to the approval of the document.
NOTE: THE CONSULTANT IS RESPONSIBLE FOR ENSURING THAT THE RECOMMENDED ALTERNATIVE COMPLIES WITH APPLICABLE STANDARDS AND CRITERIA.
REQUIRED VARIANCES WILL BE IDENTIFIED.
A5.3 ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT STATEMENT The Consultant shall compile the DEIS in accordance with the then-current provisions of the following laws, regulations, and standards, as well as any others that may then apply: NEPA and its implementing regulations, CDOT's Environmental Stewardship Guide (ESG), the USDOT Order 5610.1E, the FHWA Federal-Aid Highway Program Manual (FHPM), FHWA and FTA Regulations for Environmental Impact Statements and Related Procedures (23 CFR Part 771-777), FTA Section 5309 New Starts Criteria (includes updates on New Starts Criteria as specified in TEA-21) as applicable, the Technical Advisory T 6640.8A, and the Council on Environmental Quality's (CEQ) Regulations and guidance (40 CFR Part 1500 et seq, as amended.
The Consultant shall ensure that the general design characteristics presented in the Basic Engineering Design/EIS are practical, feasible and economical.
Design of the project will be completed sufficiently so that design standards and criteria may be evaluated and a cost estimate prepared prior to the approval of the documents.
A5.4 SURVEY PLATS The Professional Land Surveyor Consultant who sets a monument shall prepare and file a plat in accordance with Section 1, 38-51-107 Colorado Revised Statutes, as amended.
A copy of the plat and filing shall also be submitted to the CDOT/PM.
79
A5.5 DESIGN The Consultant shall submit the EDR plan set with a written response to each item discussed for each plan review.
B. DATA REQUIREMENTS B6.1 PROJECT DEVELOPMENT The following field survey data must be submitted if produced during the work: 1.
Handwritten field notes.
This shall be the original notes that have been sealed and signed by the supervising Professional Land Surveyor registered with the Colorado State Board for Professional Engineers and Land Surveyors.
Legible sealed and signed copies of the original field notes may be submitted in lieu of the original field notes only if approved by the CDOT/PM.
2.
Electronic field data.
Prior to collecting data by electronic means the Consultant shall submit a sample and receive approval to continue the work.
A sealed and signed hard copy shall be submitted with all electronic data.
Electronic data shall comply with the requirements outlined below.
3.
Photogrammetric Data.
Prior to generating mapping data the Consultant shall submit a sample of data and receive approval to continue work.
Submit a sealed and signed hard copy (map sheets when appropriate) with all electronic data.
C. PLANS REQUIREMENTS The Consultant shall follow the requirements for plans, specifications and map sheets listed below: 1.
Plans and specifications shall comply with the FHPM 6-3-3-1, "Guidelines for Preparation of Plans, Specifications, and Estimates."
(U.S. Department of Transportation, Federal Highway Administration, Federal-Aid Highway Program Manual Volume 6, Chapter 3, Section 3, subsection 1, appendix) 2.
Plan and map sheets shall comply with the following requirements: a.
The original sheets shall be size D. Size D dimensions will be 22 inches by 34 inches, and the maximum size of the content, including the border, shall be 20 inches by 31.5 inches.
Engineering Design Review Plan sets shall also be submitted in Half Size format (11 inches by 17 inches). b.
The sheets shall be full transparencies of vellum, mylar, or linen material with no paste-ons or background from paste-ons in second-generation transparencies.
The material shall be approved by the PMT prior to submission.
80
NOTE: Originals produced by the Sepia (or Diazo developing) process are not acceptable due to inconsistent quality.
c. Drawings with colors must be reproducible by printing media in black and white.
d.
All drafting and lettering shall be of the proper density and legibility for a 50 percent reduction during reproduction.
There shall be no excessive screening on drawings.
When required, screening shall be accomplished by a 50 percent screen with a maximum of 50 lines per inch.
Also, final drawings for reproduction will have all of the drafting work and image on one side of the sheet.
The consultant without additional compensation will replace plan sheets that do not comply with the above criteria.
e. Plan/map sheets shall have the CDOT "title," "revision," and "as constructed" blocks in the upper right hand corner.
Please refer to the CDOT Drafting Manual for specific details.
3.
The Consultant shall develop a project-specific original plan sheet and shall submit an example of an original plan sheet and receive approval from the PMT prior to drafting the plans.
4.
When designated in Part 1 the Consultant shall submit rectified photography (at the designated approximate scale) with Mylar original plan sheets.
5.
When approved by the PMT, original plans or mapping may be submitted on a continuous roll at an agreed width.
D. ELECTRONIC DATA SUBMITTALS All material must be submitted to the PMT in a format approved by the PMT.
Acceptance of submitted material is the sole responsibility of the PMT.
D5.1 ELECTRONIC MEDIA Software used by CDOT includes: Earthwork: Drafting: Survey: Geometry: Bridge: Estimating: MxRoad or an approved substitute AutoCAD TMOSS (developed by CDOT to convert total Station survey to format.)
CDOT COGO (Coordinate Geometry) Staff Bridge software shall be used in either design or design check Transport (a bid analysis and management systems, an AASHTO-sponsored software)
81
Specifications:
Microsoft Word
D5.2 COMPUTER DATA COMPATIBILITY CDOT utilizes two data formats which Consultants shall be required to use for submitting survey, photogrammetry, and design data: TMOSS (Topography Modeling Survey System) and MxRoad or an approved design substitute.
The data format used by the Consultant to submit surveying and photogrammetric data shall be as determined by the PMT in coordination with the respective Region PLS.
The data format for submitting design computer files shall be compatible with the CDOT MxRoad program.
The Consultant shall immediately notify the PMT if the firm is unable to produce the desired format for any reason and cease work until the problem(s) is (are) resolved.
